{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5991dd8a-37ea-48d0-bd9e-8421798c6cdb","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues I found:\n\n## 1. Deeply Nested Import Chain\n`EvalHeavy.csproj` → `level1.props` → `level2.props` → `level3.props`\n\nEach `<Import>` requires the evaluator to open, parse, and evaluate another file. While 3 levels is manageable, this pattern scales poorly and adds disk I/O during evaluation.\n\n## 2. Expensive Property Function — File I/O at Evaluation Time\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nThis calls `File.ReadAllText` **during evaluation**, not during build execution. Property functions that perform I/O block the evaluator and bypass caching. This runs on every evaluation (IDE load, restore, build).\n\n## 3. Overly Broad Glob (`**\\*.*`)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nA recursive wildcard glob forces the evaluator to walk the entire directory tree. On large repos this is extremely expensive — MSBuild must stat every file to build the item list. This also invalidates the evaluation cache whenever *any* file changes.\n\n---\n\n**Recommendations:**\n- Replace the `ReadAllText` property function with a target-time task (e.g., `ReadLinesFromFile`).\n- Narrow the glob to specific extensions or subdirectories (e.g., `**\\*.txt`).\n- Flatten or reduce the import chain where possible, or consolidate into a single `.props` file.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c92a5a6b-0822-4f68-bc00-967d1f2470b4","outputTokens":389,"requestId":"F021:C87BE:26D147E:2B1275F:69F9452E"},"id":"201c4e56-bfa0-49e8-9ab2-f3b77d30669a","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:17:45.135Z","parentId":"33c4a463-ced8-4211-b6a4-d7f2be1129a5"}
